PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK--Chicago's spot gasoline premium widened sharply on Thursday amid increased buying led by a regional refiner and a global trading company. Traders doing business in the region said BP PLC BP sold prompt conventional-blendstock for oxygenate blending, or CBOB, at 41 cents a gallon above the October Nymex benchmark price, which was 10 cents higher than Wednesday's high trade. Marathon Petroleum Corp. MPC and Shell Oil Co.'s trading company, Stusco, were among the buyers, the traders said, adding that Marathon shut a crude unit at its Robinson refinery in Illinois.

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Marathon Petroleum Corp. MPC has started to use small amounts of crude oil from the Utica shale at its refinery in Canton, Ohio, the company said Tuesday. The refinery would be among the first to process oil from the up-and-coming shale formation in the northeast U.S. The Utica is expected to grow in prominence as new drilling technology helps unlock oil and gas that had previously been too uneconomical to make drilling worth the effort. The 73,000 barrel-a-day Canton refinery will increase its take of Utica oil to up to 12,000 barrels a day in early 2012 and could raise the amount further, said Marathon Petroleum Senior Vice President Mike Palmer.

Headlines.Headline: Marathon Petroleum To Join S&P 500 Index

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Standard & Poor's said Thursday it would move Marathon Petroleum Corp., the downstream business of Marathon Oil Corp. MRO, to its S&P 500 index, replacing consumer electronics seller RadioShack Corp. RSH. Marathon Petroleum, officially set to become its own company at the end of the month, will operate six refineries having a combined capacity of 1.1 million barrels a day. Marathon Oil, meanwhile, will remain in the S&P 500 index following the spin-off. RadioShack will replace marketer Harte-Hanks Inc.
